      "type": "headline",
      "text": "Widow's Application for Army Pension.",
      "bbox": {
        "x": 0,
        "y": 10,
        "width": 100,
        "height": 10
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "This Army Pension Declaration must be executed before a Judge or Clerk of a Court of Record. In Deputy Clerk will not answer; and if before the Judge, the Clerk thereof will certify and declare official capacity and signature, and effect the same under the seal of the Court.",
      "bbox": {
        "x": 0,
        "y": 20,
        "width": 100,
        "height": 30
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "All of the State of Kentucky County of Henderson SS.",
      "bbox": {
        "x": 0,
        "y": 50,
        "width": 100,
        "height": 10
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "On this 21st day of August A.D. 1867 personally appeared before me (1) Clerk of the (2) County Court of Record, within and for the County and State aforesaid, Mrs. Rose Chambers, a resident of the (3) County of Henderson in the State of Kentucky, aged Sixty six years, who, being first duly sworn according to law, doth on her oath make the following declaration, in order to obtain the benefit of the provision made by the act of Congress, approved (4) July 4th 1866 That she is the widow of Aaron Chambers deceased, who was Private in Company \"F\", commanded by Captain John C. Moore in the 118th Regiment of (5) United States Colored Infantry, commanded by Colonel Moon in the war of 1861, and who died at White in the service aforesaid, in Field Hospital in the State of Virginia on or about the sixth day of November A.D. 1869, from (1) Decatur, incurred in the service aforesaid and while in the line of his duty, (3)",
      "bbox": {
        "x": 0,
        "y": 60,
        "width": 100,
        "height": 60
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "She further declares that she was married to the said Aaron Chambers in the (2) County of Henderson in the State of Kentucky on the 15th day of March in the year 1837, and that her name before her said marriage was Rose Black that her husband, the aforesaid Aaron Chambers died on the day above mentioned, and that she has remained a widow ever since that period, as will more fully appear by reference to the proof herewith accompanying or to be hereafter filed. She also declares that she has not, in any manner, been engaged in, or aided or abetted, the rebellion in the United States. She is commonly appointed her attorney, with full power of substitution and priscation on his part in her said behalf, and authorizes him to receive the Pension Certificate when issued. Her Post Office is at Henderson in the County of Henderson in the State of Kentucky. That her domicile or place of abode is (3) on Road Bradbury from Anderson County, East Henderson County, to Mouth of Green River by 3 miles from Armley Place.",
      "bbox": {
        "x": 0,
        "y": 120,
        "width": 100,
        "height": 60
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "I wish all communication concerning this claim sent to myself as above. That (10) there are no children now living under the age of sixteen years born to the above mentioned soldier dead while he lived together as man & wife.",
      "bbox": {
        "x": 0,
        "y": 180,
        "width": 100,
        "height": 20
      }
    },
